properties.info: Off the coast of Florida covering the seafloor are many meadows of seagrass. This plant often grows at shallower depths so it can feed off of light from the sun. Like land plants, seagrasses produce oxygen and are a source of food for many sea creatures including fish, crabs, and sea turtles. Because of their importance to ocean ecosystems around the world, efforts are in place to protect these underwater meadows.
properties.name: seagrass

properties.info: The shells of Sand Dollars like this one can be found on many beaches, dried out and bleached by the sun. In the ocean, these creatures use the fine velvet hairs that cover their shell to move around. They come in a variety of colors including green, blue, or purple like this one.
properties.name: sanddollar

properties.info: Queen Conch shells such as this one can be seen off the coast of Florida housing large sea snails. They are one of the largest molluscs to inhabit the tropical northwestern Atlantic.
properties.name: conchshell

The fish is target by several fisheries and its diet consists of many different kinds of fish including shrimp and porcupine fish.
